<div id="mount"></div> 
As you can see, this feels like a proper little local and it has its very loyal regulars.

One of these regulars has proven to be more loyal than most though.

Back in the 1920s, a meat broker by the name of Charlie, used to come here after he finished his day’s work at Smithfield Market. It’s only a stone’s throw from here so nothing unusual there.

He was a red-haired gentleman with a long moustache and he’d sit at one of the tables at the far end there and have himself a pint of mild.

Even on days he wasn’t working, he’d take the walk down here from Islington, where he lived, occupy that same spot and have a few pints of mild.

Every day, Charlie would be here. All the landlords and landladies over the years knew him well. He’d bring in any meat he hadn’t sold at the end of the day and they’d put it in pies.

He was a sociable sort of chap. Knew all the other regulars of course. They’d talk about work, about their families, their wives, the Arsenal. Regular sort of stuff.

Then one day in the mid 1930s, the landlord at the time, who went by the name One-Eyed Pete (nobody knows how he got this nickname because he had two perfectly good eyes), he was reading the local newspaper when he came across an obituary for Charlie. Died of a sickness of the liver, aged 38, will be much missed by his good mother, sister, nieces and nephews.

One-Eyed Pete was sad to hear the news, of course, but more than that he was confused and even in a state of disbelief because, when he looked up from his newspaper, there was Charlie sat in his usual spot with his usual pint of mild.

One-Eyed Pete didn’t know what to say or do. How could you ask a man if he was, in fact, dead? And what if Charlie had faked his own death and didn’t want anyone to know? So, One-Eyed Pete did what any true Englishman would do and just kept on with his day as if nothing had happened. He decided to play along.

The years went by and Charlie kept coming in every day as he always had done. Eventually, One-Eyed Pete died himself. World War Two broke out. A lot of the regulars got sent off to fight and much of the area was bombed by the Luftwaffe. Everyone forgot about Charlie.

But after the war, people would still see a man with red hair and a long moustache appearing somewhere in the pub with a pint of mild in his hand, smiling.

Ready to see if Charlie’s still here?

