<main><div id="mount"></div> 
So this estate was built in the 1950s and 1960s. It took a long time. As I mentioned before this whole area was bombed very badly in the Second World War and there was a sudden need for affordable housing.

But when they first announced the plan to build this estate, the architects received a strange letter from a very respectable man (a professor at Oxford University) who warned them that this land was an ancient Anglo-Saxon burial ground and that they should cease development.

At first, they thought he was playing a trick on them. How could an intelligent, rational man in the twentieth century believe there could be any issue building on some pagan burial ground. There was a major housing crisis and they had more pressing issues to address than some crackpot theory.

The man insisted that they abandon the works at least until the site could be fully excavated and any remains unearthed and reburied according to the rites of the time.

He even travelled down from Oxford to visit them in person. In the end, they had to file a restraining order against the man.

They felt sorry for him, thinking he had completely lost his mind.

And of course they went ahead with construction.

Everything seemed to be fine. People moved in. The architects won awards for their design. The estate was profiled as the great watermark of post-war recovery.

But the children who lived on the estate started saying they’d seen strange things at night.

They said they’d seen a mysterious figure - small with long hair - standing under the big tree on the green, from their windows at night.

A child.

Some of the bravest children would sneak out of their flats to try to
get closer to it. As soon as they’d approach, it would take off running so they couldn’t get a good look at its face.

Some of them - the very bravest - would run after it and those that did all said that it would run down to this area and it was here, among these shadows, that it would disappear.

So what do you think? Shall give it a try?

